---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'About classactionsettlementcalc.com | Free Class Action Settlement Calculator';
const description = 'About classactionsettlementcalc.com — how we calculate individual class action settlement shares, our editorial standards, and how the site is funded.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>About classactionsettlementcalc.com</h1>
  <p>classactionsettlementcalc.com is a free class action resource maintained by The Click Lab. Our settlement calculator and guides help class members figure out roughly what their individual payout might look like once a settlement is distributed &mdash; and just as often, help them understand why a headline settlement number almost never matches what actually lands in a claimant's account. The Site is built for someone who received a class action notice or found their name connected to a settled case and wants a plain-English starting point before deciding whether to file a claim, opt out, or ignore it.</p>

  <h2>What we do</h2>
  <p>We translate settlement administration mechanics &mdash; attorney fee awards, administration costs, claims filing rates, and plans of allocation &mdash; into a plain-English calculator and guides. Every page is reviewed by our <a href="/editorial/">editorial team</a> with citations to published settlement administration data and court-approved allocation plans. The calculator takes the gross settlement amount, estimated class size, claims filing rate, allocation method, and named-plaintiff status, and models the net fund and per-claimant share those inputs typically produce.</p>

  <h2>Who this calculator is for</h2>
  <p>Most visitors fall into one of a few groups: class members who received a settlement notice or postcard and want to know what a realistic payout range looks like before deciding whether filing a claim is worth their time; people trying to understand why a "$500 million settlement" produced a $12 check; class members weighing whether opting out and pursuing an individual claim could ever make sense; and named plaintiffs curious about how an incentive award factors into the total. We built the Site around these use cases, which is why every guide leads with a plain-English answer before it gets into allocation-plan detail.</p>

  <h2>How the estimate is built</h2>
  <p>The full mechanics &mdash; how the net fund is derived after attorney fees and administration costs, how claims filing rates vary by case type, and how equal, pro-rata, tiered, and coupon allocation methods change an individual share &mdash; are documented on our <a href="/methodology/">methodology page</a>. At a high level: the calculator reduces the gross settlement by a typical fee-and-cost percentage, divides the remaining net fund by the number of class members expected to actually file a claim at the given claims rate, and adjusts the result for the selected allocation method and named-plaintiff status.</p>

  <h2>What we don&rsquo;t do</h2>
  <p>We don't provide legal advice, and nothing on this Site creates an attorney-client relationship. What you personally will receive from a specific settlement depends on the court-approved plan of allocation, the actual claims rate once the filing deadline passes, and case-specific facts our calculator can't see &mdash; variables that routinely move a real payout above or below a generic estimate. We also don't evaluate individual claims, tell you whether you qualify for a specific settlement, estimate what a named case will actually pay, or file claims on anyone's behalf. For questions about a specific settlement, the claims administrator named in your class notice is the authoritative source; see our <a href="/contact/">contact page</a> for more on when that's the right place to go instead of us.</p>

  <h2>Editorial standards</h2>
  <p>Every guide and reference page is written from primary sources &mdash; published settlement administration data, court orders approving plans of allocation, and procedural rules governing class actions &mdash; and reviewed before publication. We don't publish thin content: each page is meant to answer a specific question a class member would actually ask, with enough detail to be useful when a notice shows up in the mail. Our full editorial workflow, contributor backgrounds, and sourcing policy are on the <a href="/editorial/">editorial team page</a>.</p>

  <h2>How we make money</h2>
  <p>Display advertising via Google AdSense funds our editorial content, and we don't accept paid placements or favorable mentions in our guides &mdash; no law firm or settlement administrator pays to influence what we write. Separately, the Site offers an optional case-review form: if you submit it, your name, phone, email, and case details are shared with attorneys who may compensate The Click Lab Agency LLC for the referral. That's a disclosed advertising product, not an editorial endorsement, and using it is always optional. See our <a href="/privacy/">privacy policy</a> for details on data handling and what's shared if you use the form.</p>

  <h2>Contact</h2>
  <p>Questions, corrections, or feedback: see our <a href="/contact/">contact page</a>.</p>
</BaseLayout>
